background/general description: the world bank group’s vision and strategy
the global development community is at an auspicious turning point in history. thanks to the success of the past few decades and favorable economic growth, developing countries now have an unprecedented opportunity to end extreme poverty within a generation. this is the vision of the wbg: to eradicate extreme poverty by reducing the number of people living on less than $1.25 a day to 3 percent by 2030 and promote shared prosperity by fostering the income growth of the bottom 40 percent in every country.
to achieve this vision, the wbg board of governors has approved a strategy for the organization. this strategy leverages, for the first time, the combined strength of the wbg institutions and their unique ability to partner with the public and private sectors to deliver customized development solutions backed by finance, world class knowledge and convening services. the strategy has three components: (1) maximizing development impact by engaging country clients in identifying and tackling the most difficult development challenges; (2) promoting scaled-up partnerships that are strategically aligned with the goals; and (3) crowding in public and private resources, expertise and ideas.
the architecture underpinning the strategy and instrumental to its success is the establishment of fourteen global practices and five global themes that, in concert with the wbg regions, will design solutions that address clients’ most pressing developmental challenges, and ultimately, enable the wbg to meet its twin goals of eliminating extreme poverty and boosting shared prosperity.
organizational context
like most organizations in the 21st century, the world bank is knowledge-intensive. our experience and expertise are our products, delivered through project implementation insights from supervision reports as well as well as thought-provoking analytical work. in both our country offices and corporate offices reside individuals who are sought-after experts in their field and who are contributing daily to the bank’s twin goals of eliminating extreme poverty and promoting shared prosperity for all. the bank has a 70+ year history of gathering and storing the output of efforts to further the development agenda. we attract the best and brightest; recruited to work alongside equally bright individuals. providing those individuals with strong infrastructure and support to manage knowledge so that they can concentrate on delivering quality and outstanding service to our country clients is deckm’s commitment.
unit context
the development economics knowledge management is a cross-cutting area within the world bank, working across 14 global practices, 5 cross-cutting solution areas, 6 regions and corporate functions. deckm takes the lead in ensuring operational knowledge flows across operations in support of the bank’s development agenda.
as a newly formed unit within development economics (dec), deckm continues to build its program of services and offerings. the functions that make up deckm include:
text/data analytics: offering up insights through text and data analytics and capturing, curating and disseminating knowledge through research, literature reviews to support decision-making by both operations staff and senior management.
knowledge management: ensuring operational knowledge is flowing across operations; including country management units, global practices and global themes in support of the bank’s development agenda;
learning: ensuring operational best practices and lessons learned are captured in our learning curriculum to be delivered via our open learning campus platform;
global delivery initiative: collaboratively creating a collective and cumulative evidence base of delivery of know-how (global delivery initiative) to inform development practice and improve implementation results.
south-south exchange facility: an integrated knowledge sharing approach to transfer knowledge from one country to another.
background & general description:
this role leads both a function and a team within the bank that uses technology to identify patterns, draw insights from text and data, uses predictive analytics to assist in decision-making and develops the algorithms powering machine learning. it also includes extracting from various available archived documents relevant tacit knowledge insights on topics that could enrich the project design , delivery and implementation process by bank teams. the technical solutions developed by this team will help to address business and knowledge-related issues experienced by, primarily but not limited to, our operations group. this important role will lead the tda team in working with cutting edge technologies to harness existing codified data in the world bank and leverage artificial intelligence, deep learning and machine learning capabilities to ultimately advance the development agenda.
this role sits within the deckm (development economics knowledge management) team and reports to the km program lead. the individual in this strategic role leads the text & data analytics (tda) team based in chennai, india. working closely with the team lead in place in chennai, the senior data scientist will use their strategic vision and planning skills to take the team to the next level. the senior data scientist is in a program lead position and works closely with all deckm units, internal clients and other key stakeholders.
the text and data analytics team is the off-shoring unit established to provide intelligent knowledge -based solutions for operations. the senior data scientist will also lead the effort to explore and establish additional services to be provided by the chennai team in support of operations. currently, some initial forays have been made into providing content management and research support. potential areas for exploration include content management, anonymization, and community of practice moderation. consultation with companies and organizations in chennai, delhi, and hyderabad will help to provide insight into what might be possible. subsequent consultation with wbg operations will then match supply with demand.
